'''Mihail Lascăr''' ([[November 8]], [[1889]], [[Târgu Jiu]] &ndash; [[July 24]], [[1959]], [[Bucharest]]) was a [[Romania]]n General duting [[World War II]]. 

On [[January 10]], [[1941]], he was appointed commanding officer of the First Mountain Brigade, an elite military unit of the 
[[Third Army (Romania)|Third Army]]. In June 1941, he took part in [[Operation Barbarossa]] (the invasion of the Soviet Union by [[Nazi Germany]], in which Romanian troops, under the command of Marshal [[Ion Antonescu]], participated; ''see [[Romania during World War II]]'').  During that period, the First Mountain Brigade operated in [[Bukovina|Northern Bukovina]]. Lascăr remained in charge of this unit until [[February 10]], [[1942]]. On [[March 11]], [[1942]], he took charge of the 6th Romanian Division on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], and fought at the [[Romanian Armies in the Battle of Stalingrad|Battle of Stalingrad]].  He was taken prisoner on [[November 22]], [[1942]], spending the years 1943-1945 in captivity in the [[Soviet Union]]. 

On [[April 12]], [[1945]], Lascăr became commander of the [[Horia, Cloşca şi Crişan Division]], which he led until [[September 12]], [[1945]], when he was named commander of the [[Fourth Army (Romania)|Fourth Army]].  On [[November 29]], [[1946]], he became [[Minister of Defense]], staying in that post until [[December 27]], [[1947]]. He was then Inspector of the Armed Forces until [[January 12]], [[1950]], when he retired.

==Awards==
In January 1942, he received the [[Iron Cross]], 1st class and the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross|Knight's Cross]]. 
On [[December 31]], [[1942]], he was decorated with the [[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd class.

